description.plain:
Andy Shauf is a Canadian singer-songwriter and multi-instrumentalist from Regina, Saskatchewan. He is mostly self-taught musician, accessing instruments at a young age through the Radio Shack outlet run by his parents. Born to a evangelical Christian family, Shauf began playing Christian music with his family and began professionally as a drummer for a Christian pop punk band.

He started his solo career in 2006 with his Independent release “Love and the memories of It” followed by “Grandpa Songs” in 2007.  He released  his debut album, Darker Days in 2009. Shortly after, he released two EPs, Waiting for the Sun to Leave and Sam Jones Feeds His Demons, before releasing his second studio album The Bearer of Bad News in 2012, which jump-started his career as a solo artist. Shauf’s big-break came in 2016 when he released his third studio album, The Party, to critical acclaim. It featured Shauf’s most popular song to date, “The Magician”. The album was nominated for the Polaris Music Prize and received four nominations at the Juno Awards. Shauf has been noted for his practice of recording and arranging each instrument on his albums himself.

description.plain:
Early to the party can be interpreted as a narrative of a girl arriving early to the party, she is nervous and watching everyone as they arrive and settle in. Her love interest doesn’t pay attention to her and ignores her to be with his friends.

This could also be a companion to “Quite Like You.” In which we see things in Sherry’s perspective when she arrives to the party and before “Quite Like You” takes place.

songs.title: Wendell Walker

description.plain: The narrator has a friend named Wendell Walker who hears the voice of God say the woman he is in love with is not being true to him. She is seeing another man. What he doesn’t know is that the other man is the narrator–his friend. When Wendell catches them together he prepares to shoot the narrator but is too hesitant. The narrator pushes the gun away, but while doing so, Wendell shoots his wife and kills her. Unable to live with what he has done, Wendell then shoots himself. The narrator is left in the room with two dead friends. He realizes this mess is all his fault and asks himself, “My god, my God what have I done?”

songs.title: My Dear Helen

description.plain:
In “My Dear Helen”, the narrator, an elderly man, addresses his late wife, essentially catching her up on the events of his life since she passed away.

In the latter half of the song, the narrator retells the events of the previous track, “Jerry Was a Clerk”, from a different perspective.

The narrator expresses his fear that he won’t be allowed into heaven as an “accidental murderer,” drawing a parallel between this fear and a pleasant memory from he and his wife’s early relationship, in which she met him at the gates (presumably the gates of a traveling fair or something similar) to sneak him in. He warns Helen that he may need a similar type of help if she would like him to be with her in heaven someday.

songs.title: Living Room

description.plain:
Claire, a friend/acquaintance to Charlie and the narrator shares a small vignette of her family life with the two.
About how, as a young child, she pined for her father’s attention and recognition. She even took the time to draw a picture for him.
She connects it to an experience she had with her own child, not taking the energy or time to acknowledge him properly for something he was proud of.
Although the two seem to be on close enough terms with Claire, this fairly unprompted peek into her home life leaves them bewildered. Probably because of how heavy the topic of familial love and generational trauma is.

The lyrics are from the perspective of the Christian God, who asks nonbelievers upon their arrival to heaven “Was all my love wasted on you?” In A 2016 interview, Shauf says he grew up Christian but became nonreligious in his twenties. He has touched on religion before, such as on his 2022 single “Satan”, usually with a dry sense of humor.

description.plain:
This song is about 3 guys who are planning to steal money from a farmer’s property so they can leave their boring old lives in their shitty town. Their friend jerry planned it all and had a van ready so they could get away easily.

Before they started however, Jerry brought along a girl, Mary-Anne. They were just about to get to the watertank where the money was buried, but Mary-Anne trips next to a Chicken Coup, the chickens go mental and it wakes up the Farmer. He starts to shoot at them, so they all run towards the van. 1 of them doesnt make it (Mary-Anne) and Jerry drives away selfishly, saving them and leaving Mary-Anne behind.

[In the song “My Dear Helen” it tells the story from the Farmer’s point of view, and he fires a shot thinking its a fox outside, he kills Mary-Anne and he instantly regrets it. He takes the shovel she had and buries her body with it]

songs.title: Daylight Dreaming

description.plain:
This song introduces a new character, a friend or ex-partner of Norm’s victim. This character narrates as he tows her truck out of the Halloween Store’s parking lot, trying to relive their old days of a similar prank. Norm’s victim sees this ex and knows that they’ve towed her car around the corner. Fed up with the ex’s actions, they hitch a ride with Norm instead, leading to her demise.
This character is aware that they need to leave their ex alone, and beg god for strength, but still tows her car and expects her call.

songs.title: Long Throw

description.plain:
Narrated by Norm’s victim’s ex again, this song continues a few days later at a Halloween party. This character is still reminiscing about their old days together, hoping that their ex will arrive at the party.
In the grand scheme of the album, this ex bemoaning over being left alone at a party seems mild compared to the victim’s state of being locked in their stalker’s car. Despite this, there is still a lot of pain in the uncertainty of waiting for a call, of hoping to see an old friend at a party, and never getting that closure.

description.plain:
“When I was young, there were a few years where I wasn’t allowed to celebrate Hallowe’en,” Shauf states in a press release. “The church that I grew up in was saying that Hallowe’en was ‘The Devil’s Day’ and that it had its roots in satanic rituals. After a few years of this, my parents realized it was a bit silly to deny us our free candy and let us resume.

“The Christianity that I was brought up in said that believers went to heaven and non-believers went to hell. A sort of cartoon-like simplification of ancient texts. So with the lyrics of this song, I was trying to take this cartoon-like simplification of life (and death) and pair it with a cartoon-like version of this Christian hell. Where after you complete a long and disciplined life, you find yourself holding a bite-sized chocolate bar stapled to an invitation to a Hallowe’en pool party with Satan himself.”

- Under the Radar

description.plain:
Unreleased from Shauf. I can only gather by the groom’s name being “Sam” that this is the same Sam from the “Sam Jones Feeds His Demons” EP, released by Shauf in 2015.

I found this in a streamingcafe.net stream from september 2014. I can only assume the title of the song is “The Wedding” as that’s where this song takes place. Lyrics are all added by ear, but im pretty confident I’ve got them down.

The song is about Sam at his wedding (If it is the same Sam as mentioned above, then this would be Sam and Victoria’s wedding day). Sam from the “Sam Jones Feeds His Demons” EP had a drinking problem and was very abusive, this could very well tell the start of Sams problems and abusive relationship with Victoria.

He’s not yet had his first dance with his bride, he’s too nervous, and he’s too stubborn to force himself up, so he just sits and ignores her while he drinks while all his friends leave him at the table while they dance. He gets up off his seat, while Victoria thinks hes finally going to dance with her, he walks straight out for a smoke and leaves her to sulk.
